<span id="freeTextContainer10254931927843139222">I read this book, part of my mission of reading the classics = the 1001 list. It had moments when it was a real joy, i couldnt stop reading. and then there were moments of pure boredom.<br/>Ok, Stendhal did a fantastic job presenting the &quot;realities&quot; of the society in the 19. century. all those intrigues, all those names they were quite hard to follow sometimes.<br/><br/>Now comes some sort of SPOILER <br/><br/><br/>And then it was the end, bitter and pragmatic, which remainded us that no matter what we do, how we bahave, in </span>
  <span id="freeText10254931927843139222" style="display:none">I read this book, part of my mission of reading the classics = the 1001 list. It had moments when it was a real joy, i couldnt stop reading. and then there were moments of pure boredom.<br />Ok, Stendhal did a fantastic job presenting the "realities" of the society in the 19. century. all those intrigues, all those names they were quite hard to follow sometimes.<br /><br />Now comes some sort of SPOILER <br /><br /><br />And then it was the end, bitter and pragmatic, which remainded us that no matter what we do, how we bahave, in the end we all have the same fate. young, old, beautiful, ugly, coldhearted, loving, haters, intriguemakers. Maybe that was his point all along. <br />As I said, interesting read. </span>
