<div id="review_3282804151" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3282804151" />
    <a title="Robert Cruthirds" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/12593643-robert-cruthirds"><img alt="Robert Cruthirds" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1581311040p2/12593643.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3282804151?book_show_action=true">Apr 28, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Robert Cruthirds" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Robert Cruthirds" href="/user/show/12593643-robert-cruthirds">Robert Cruthirds</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3282804151" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17457510770049029968">This novel starts out with a bang when a teenager from Parma, Italy, runs away from home to join Napoleon&apos;s forces in battle. But this is no ordinary battle - our hero Fabrizio has blundered into the French retreat from Waterloo. After much confusion, he finally joins a unit that is involved in a skirmish against the advancing Prussian forces.<br/><br/>A few somewhat amusing incidents occur before Fabrizio finally returns to Paris and begins his trek back to Parma. Shortly thereafter, he&apos;s involved in a t</span>
  <span id="freeText17457510770049029968" style="display:none">This novel starts out with a bang when a teenager from Parma, Italy, runs away from home to join Napoleon's forces in battle. But this is no ordinary battle - our hero Fabrizio has blundered into the French retreat from Waterloo. After much confusion, he finally joins a unit that is involved in a skirmish against the advancing Prussian forces.<br /><br />A few somewhat amusing incidents occur before Fabrizio finally returns to Paris and begins his trek back to Parma. Shortly thereafter, he's involved in a tussle with a group of traveling actors when a man turns up dead. <br /><br />Thus begins a series of misadventures for "our hero" Fabrizio. Stendhal observes the court intrigue in Parma and how his aunt and her lover are involved in this drama. Of course, this is really a satire or parody of life in those post-Napoleanic times in northern Italy. Stendhal is an amazing writer, although the novel can seem tedious at times with an array of characters and plot spin-offs. I get the feeling sometimes that the novel is partly a parody of itself?</span>
  <a data-text-id="17457510770049029968" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

