    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2427869711" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2427869711" />
    <a title="Sam toer" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2134028-sam-toer"><img alt="Sam toer" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2427869711?book_show_action=true">Jun 18, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sam toer" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sam toer" href="/user/show/2134028-sam-toer">Sam toer</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2427869711" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9776294968281861376">&quot;Politics, in a work of literature ,&quot; Stendhal once said , &quot;are like a pistol-shot in the middle of a concert, something crude which, nevertheless, one can&apos;t possibly ignore.&quot; Stendhal&apos;s remark explodes at point-blank in this novel &quot;The Charterhouse of Parma&quot;, the epic tale of a young French officer in the Napoleonic wars, and his aunt - a duchess of legendary beauty and resourcefulness. Unlike the darkness of the &quot;Red and Black&quot;, &quot;The Charterhouse of Parma&quot; is a comic masterpiece; a classic of </span>
  <span id="freeText9776294968281861376" style="display:none">"Politics, in a work of literature ," Stendhal once said , "are like a pistol-shot in the middle of a concert, something crude which, nevertheless, one can't possibly ignore." Stendhal's remark explodes at point-blank in this novel "The Charterhouse of Parma", the epic tale of a young French officer in the Napoleonic wars, and his aunt - a duchess of legendary beauty and resourcefulness. Unlike the darkness of the "Red and Black", "The Charterhouse of Parma" is a comic masterpiece; a classic of nineteenth century French Romanticism. A pistol- shot, indeed! Stendhal wrote it in a marathon time of only 53 days and has been a bestseller ever since its publication. Fabrizio del Dongo, the hero, is a typical young man of romantic sensibility; wild, primitive, and undisciplined, with a curious quiet mystery about his parentage in the background. He is enthralled by beautiful landscapes and senses strange affinities between his soul and a tree planted at the time of his birth. Fabrizio begins his insurrection within the family, hating his nominal father and despising his brother. He quickly carries this warfare onto the field of physical battle, at Waterloo (one of the best descriptions of the horrors of war in all French fiction). The book has plenty of action, romance, intrigue and excitement. It is an essential book in one's literary appreciation of great French classics.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9776294968281861376" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


