<div id="review_61114783" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/61114783" />
    <a title="Lobstergirl" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1910836-lobstergirl"><img alt="Lobstergirl" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1380256801p2/1910836.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/61114783?book_show_action=true">Jun 25, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lobstergirl" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lobstergirl" href="/user/show/1910836-lobstergirl">Lobstergirl</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1910836-lobstergirl?shelf=own">own</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1910836-lobstergirl?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer61114783" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15921365786216683535"><br/>Stendhal wrote this novel in 52 days. It shows.<br/><br/>Beyond that issue, it&apos;s operatic and overly melodramatic. Lovers pining for each other for hundreds of pages. Court intrigues that are hard to follow because if there are several Counts and Princes, they will each be called &quot;the prince&quot; or &quot;the Count&quot; rather than their proper name. Never mind us...we&apos;re just trying to read here...<br/><br/>It&apos;s hard to take the measure of Stendhal&apos;s tone; for the first 300 pages I couldn&apos;t tell if he was being ironic or strai</span>
  <span id="freeText15921365786216683535" style="display:none"><br />Stendhal wrote this novel in 52 days. It shows.<br /><br />Beyond that issue, it's operatic and overly melodramatic. Lovers pining for each other for hundreds of pages. Court intrigues that are hard to follow because if there are several Counts and Princes, they will each be called "the prince" or "the Count" rather than their proper name. Never mind us...we're just trying to read here...<br /><br />It's hard to take the measure of Stendhal's tone; for the first 300 pages I couldn't tell if he was being ironic or straight. I think I've figured out that some of that was irony. But stylistically he can't compare to a writer like Flaubert. (I've read <i>The Red and the Black</i> but it was awhile ago and I can't remember if it was written in the same style as this.)<br /><br />Robert Andrew Parker is a skilled illustrator; I've seen his work in The New Yorker. But his illustrations for this edition are pointless. In color, they can glow like stained glass. Here in black and white they're simply blah.<br /><br />Richard Howard's Afterword is strangely punctuated with ellipses. To what purpose? It's like he dashed it off in the back of a cab.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15921365786216683535" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


